questions.description:
An LRU cache with **capacity 3** processes this sequence (touching a key moves it to the most-recently-used end):

```js
put('A', 1);
put('B', 2);
put('C', 3);
get('A');
put('D', 4); // capacity exceeded — one key is evicted
```

A hot function memoizes results in a module-level `Map`, keyed by a unique per-request id, and never deletes anything:

```js
const cache = new Map();
function getReport(reqId, build) {
  if (!cache.has(reqId)) cache.set(reqId, build());
  return cache.get(reqId);
}
```

questions.explanation:
A JS `Map` remembers **insertion order** and exposes it cheaply, which gives you most of an LRU cache for free:

```js
function createLRU(max = 100) {
  const cache = new Map();
  return {
    get(key) {
      if (!cache.has(key)) return undefined;
      const v = cache.get(key);
      cache.delete(key);   // re-insert to move to the MRU end
      cache.set(key, v);
      return v;
    },
    set(key, v) {
      cache.delete(key);             // refresh position if already present
      cache.set(key, v);
      if (cache.size > max) {
        cache.delete(cache.keys().next().value); // evict the LRU (oldest) key
      }
    },
  };
}
```

The facts the options test: `set` on an **existing** key keeps its original position (so you must `delete` then `set` to promote it), `keys().next().value` is the least-recently-used key, and there is **no** automatic capping — the size check and eviction are your job. This bounded cache is exactly the fix for the unbounded-memo memory leak.
